    "fullDescription": "ECHELON is a signals intelligence (SIGINT) collection and analysis network operated by the Five Eyes alliance â€” the United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand â€” under the UKUSA Agreement. The foundational treaty, the British-US Communication Intelligence Agreement, was signed on 5 March 1946 to formalize wartime SIGINT cooperation, yet its very existence was not publicly acknowledged until 2005, and the full text was not declassified until June 2010 when GCHQ and NSA released it to their respective national archives. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nECHELON was formally established in 1971 to monitor Soviet and Eastern Bloc military and diplomatic communications during the Cold War. The system operates through a network of ground stations and satellites capable of intercepting telephone calls, faxes, emails, and other electronic communications on a global scale. Each Five Eyes member nation operates interception facilities and shares collected intelligence, an arrangement that critics have long argued allows each nation to circumvent domestic legal prohibitions on surveilling its own citizens by having partner nations collect that data instead. [ðŸŸ¡]\n\nThe first major public disclosure came in August 1972 when former NSA analyst Perry Fellwock, writing under the pseudonym Winslow Peck in Ramparts magazine, revealed the existence and scope of NSA surveillance operations. [ðŸŸ¡] In 1988, former Lockheed Martin contractor Margaret Newsham told a closed session of the US Congress that ECHELON was intercepting the phone calls of US politicians, including Senator Strom Thurmond. [ðŸŸ¡] New Zealand journalist Nicky Hager's 1996 book Secret Power provided the first comprehensive public account of the ECHELON system, based on extensive insider sources, and directly prompted the European Parliament investigation. [ðŸŸ¡]\n\nIn 2001, the European Parliament's Temporary Committee on the ECHELON Interception System produced report A5-0264/2001, adopted by a vote of 367 to 159. The committee concluded that the existence of ECHELON was \"no longer in doubt\" and found that its purpose extended to intercepting private and commercial communications â€” not merely military targets. The investigation documented economic espionage: US intelligence reportedly intercepted communications related to a $6 billion Airbus contract with Saudi Arabia (benefiting Boeing/McDonnell Douglas) and a $1.3 billion Thomson-CSF bid in Brazil (benefiting Raytheon). [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nEdward Snowden's 2013 disclosures, including GCHQ and NSA documents referencing the \"ECHELON agreement\" by name, confirmed and vastly expanded public understanding of Five Eyes surveillance capabilities, validating decades of whistleblower testimony and investigative journalism. [ðŸŸ¢]",
