    "fullDescription": "NSO Group, founded in 2010 in Herzliya, Israel, developed Pegasus â€” a military-grade zero-click spyware capable of remotely compromising smartphones (iOS and Android) without any user interaction. Once deployed, Pegasus gains full access to messages, emails, photos, cameras, microphones, passwords, location data, and encrypted communications including Signal and WhatsApp. [ðŸŸ¢] Citizen Lab first publicly documented Pegasus in 2016 and has since tracked its deployment across 45+ countries, identifying sophisticated exploit chains including FORCEDENTRY and BLASTPASS that leveraged zero-day vulnerabilities in Apple's iMessage framework.\n\nIn July 2021, the Pegasus Project â€” a consortium of 17 media organizations coordinated by Forbidden Stories with technical analysis by Amnesty International's Security Lab â€” revealed a leaked list of over 50,000 phone numbers selected as potential surveillance targets by NSO's government clients. [ðŸŸ¡] Forensic analysis confirmed infections on devices belonging to journalists, human rights defenders, lawyers, political leaders, and diplomats across 50+ countries. Confirmed targets included French President Emmanuel Macron, Al Jazeera journalists, associates of murdered Washington Post contributor Jamal Khashoggi, Indian opposition politicians, and Mexican journalists â€” several of whom were subsequently murdered. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nLegal consequences have mounted. WhatsApp (Meta) sued NSO Group in October 2019 for compromising approximately 1,400 users; in December 2024, a federal judge found NSO liable under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, and a jury subsequently awarded $167.25 million in punitive damages. [ðŸŸ¢] Apple filed a separate lawsuit in November 2021 seeking a permanent injunction against NSO's use of Apple products. [ðŸŸ¢] The U.S. Commerce Department placed NSO Group on its Entity List on November 3, 2021, determining the company's tools had been used to \"maliciously target\" government officials, journalists, and activists. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nNSO maintains it sells exclusively to vetted government clients for lawful intelligence and counter-terrorism purposes and claims no visibility into specific targets â€” assertions repeatedly contradicted by forensic evidence. [ðŸŸ¢] Critically, all Pegasus export licenses must be approved by Israel's Ministry of Defense under the Defense Export Controls Agency (DECA), making the Israeli state a de facto gatekeeper of the technology's global proliferation. [ðŸŸ¢] This arrangement represents a privatization of signals intelligence capabilities historically monopolized by state agencies, echoing but commercializing the surveillance architecture of programs like ECHELON â€” now deployable by any government willing to pay. [ðŸ”´]",
