    "fullDescription": "Substantial evidence demonstrates that US intelligence agencies possessed advance warning of Japanese hostile intentions prior to the December 7, 1941 attack on Pearl Harbor, and that critical intelligence was withheld from field commanders.\n\nThe United States had broken Japanese diplomatic codes under the program codenamed MAGIC, enabling Washington analysts to read high-level Japanese communications in near real-time [ðŸŸ¢]. Key intercepts in late November and early December 1941 indicated Japan was preparing for imminent military action, including a 14-part diplomatic message and a deadline of November 29 after which \"things are automatically going to happen\" [ðŸŸ¢]. These intercepts circulated among senior Washington officials but were not forwarded to Admiral Husband Kimmel and General Walter Short at Pearl Harbor [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nThe McCollum Memo, written October 7, 1940 by Lt. Commander Arthur McCollum of the Office of Naval Intelligence, outlined an eight-point plan to provoke Japan into committing an overt act of war. Proposed actions included trade embargoes, fleet repositioning, and material support to China [ðŸŸ¢]. Declassified in 1994, its significance remains debated â€” historians disagree on whether FDR saw the document, though several of the eight actions were subsequently implemented [ðŸŸ¡].\n\nThe \"Winds Code\" â€” a Japanese instruction that certain weather broadcast phrases would signal the breaking of relations with specific nations â€” was reportedly intercepted before the attack, but its handling and even its existence in intercepted form remain disputed [ðŸŸ¡].\n\nKimmel and Short were relieved of command and publicly blamed. Both repeatedly requested courts-martial to clear their names but were denied [ðŸŸ¢]. Between 1944 and 1946, eight investigations produced conflicting conclusions. The Roberts Commission (1942) has been criticized for its rushed proceedings and narrow focus on field commanders while ignoring Washington's intelligence failures [ðŸŸ¢]. In 1999, the Senate passed a resolution recommending posthumous restoration of Kimmel and Short's ranks, finding they had been denied vital intelligence, though multiple presidents declined to act [ðŸŸ¢]. Robert Stinnett's \"Day of Deceit\" (2000), based on FOIA-obtained documents, argued FDR deliberately provoked and permitted the attack; his thesis remains contested among historians [ðŸŸ¡].",
