    "description": "Ruby Ridge (1992) and the Waco siege (1993) represent defining case studies in federal law enforcement overreach, excessive use of force, and systemic accountability failures within the FBI, ATF, and US Marshals Service.\n\nAt Ruby Ridge, Idaho, in August 1992, a US Marshals surveillance operation on the Weaver family property escalated into a firefight that killed Deputy Marshal William Degan and 14-year-old Sammy Weaver [ðŸŸ¢].",
    "fullDescription": "Ruby Ridge (1992) and the Waco siege (1993) represent defining case studies in federal law enforcement overreach, excessive use of force, and systemic accountability failures within the FBI, ATF, and US Marshals Service.\n\nAt Ruby Ridge, Idaho, in August 1992, a US Marshals surveillance operation on the Weaver family property escalated into a firefight that killed Deputy Marshal William Degan and 14-year-old Sammy Weaver [ðŸŸ¢]. The following day, FBI Hostage Rescue Team sniper Lon Horiuchi shot and killed Vicki Weaver as she stood in the cabin doorway holding her infant daughter [ðŸŸ¢]. The modified Rules of Engagement authorizing deadly force were later found to be unconstitutional by a DOJ task force review [ðŸŸ¢]. Randy Weaver was acquitted of all serious charges at trial, and the federal government ultimately paid a $3.1 million settlement to the Weaver family [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nAt Waco, Texas, on February 28, 1993, the ATF attempted to execute a search warrant on the Branch Davidian compound. The raid devolved into a gun battle that killed four ATF agents and six Branch Davidians, triggering a 51-day standoff [ðŸŸ¢]. On April 19, the FBI launched a final assault using CS gas delivered by Combat Engineering Vehicles. A fire engulfed the compound, killing 76 people including 25 children [ðŸŸ¢]. The Danforth Report (2000), produced by Special Counsel John Danforth, concluded the government did not start the fire or shoot at Davidians during the final assault, but confirmed the FBI had initially denied and later admitted using pyrotechnic tear gas rounds [ðŸŸ¢]. The Treasury Department's own internal review sharply criticized ATF leadership for the botched initial raid and subsequent cover-up attempts [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nCongressional hearings in 1995 exposed significant disputes over who fired first at Waco, the appropriateness of the Rules of Engagement, and whether inserting CS gas â€” a chemical agent banned in warfare â€” was justifiable given the known presence of children [ðŸŸ¢]. Notably, FBI sniper Lon Horiuchi, who killed Vicki Weaver at Ruby Ridge, was also deployed at Waco [ðŸŸ¢]. Both events became powerful grievance symbols and directly motivated the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing; Timothy McVeigh explicitly cited Waco as his primary motivation [ðŸŸ¢]. Together, these sieges exposed a pattern of militarized federal operations, inadequate oversight, and institutional resistance to accountability.",
