    "fullDescription": "From 1972 to 1995, the U.S. intelligence community funded a sustained research and operational program investigating remote viewing â€” the claimed ability to perceive distant targets using anomalous cognition. The effort operated under a succession of classified codenames: SCANATE (1972), GONDOLA WISH (1977), GRILL FLAME (1978), CENTER LANE (1983), SUN STREAK (1986), and finally STARGATE (1991) [ðŸŸ¢]. Research was conducted primarily at Stanford Research Institute (SRI International) in Menlo Park, California, by laser physicists Dr. Harold Puthoff and Russell Targ, under contract to the CIA and later the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA). Over the program's lifetime, approximately $20 million was expended [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nThe program produced several notable remote viewers. Ingo Swann, widely credited as the co-developer of the Coordinate Remote Viewing (CRV) protocol, conducted a 1973 session on Jupiter in which he described features â€” including a planetary ring â€” that were not confirmed until Voyager 1 arrived in 1979 [ðŸŸ¡]. Pat Price, a former police commissioner, reportedly described structural details of a Soviet weapons research facility at Semipalatinsk from map coordinates alone, producing sketches of a large gantry crane and a spherical containment vessel that correlated with later intelligence [ðŸŸ¢]. Army Chief Warrant Officer Joseph McMoneagle (Remote Viewer #001) was awarded the Legion of Merit upon retirement; his declassified citation credits him with providing \"critical intelligence unavailable from any other source\" to the DIA, NSA, CIA, Secret Service, and Joint Chiefs of Staff [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nHundreds of operational intelligence collection sessions were conducted for multiple agencies, including CIA, DIA, NSA, DEA, and the U.S. Secret Service [ðŸŸ¢]. The program was terminated in 1995 after Congress directed a formal evaluation. The American Institutes for Research (AIR) review, led by Dr. Michael Mumford, included independent assessments by statistician Jessica Utts and psychologist Ray Hyman. Utts concluded the statistical evidence was robust, writing that the results \"would be widely accepted if it pertained to something more mundane.\" Hyman agreed the effects were statistically anomalous but argued the methodology was insufficient to establish a paranormal explanation [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nThe CIA subsequently declassified approximately 89,000 pages of Stargate records, now accessible through the CIA FOIA Electronic Reading Room (CREST) [ðŸŸ¢]. Despite the program's official closure, multiple former participants and program managers â€” including McMoneagle and former program director Dale Graff â€” have publicly stated that operational remote viewing capability continued under different organizational auspices after 1995 [ðŸŸ¡].",
