    "fullDescription": "Special Access Programs (SAPs) are security protocols established under DoD Directive 5205.07 (originally issued 2010, updated 2020) that impose need-to-know access controls beyond standard Top Secret/SCI classification. SAPs are divided into 'acknowledged' (existence can be confirmed) and 'unacknowledged' (USAP â€” existence itself is classified). A critical subcategory is 'waived' USAPs, which are exempted from the normal Congressional notification requirement under 10 U.S.C. Section 119, meaning only the 'Big Eight' (chairs and ranking members of defense and intelligence committees) are briefed â€” and in some interpretations, even this notification can be limited. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nThe FY2023 combined national intelligence and military intelligence budgets totaled approximately $71.7 billion in classified spending ($67.1B NIP + supplemental MIP), per the Office of the Director of National Intelligence. The total classified 'black budget' has grown substantially since the post-9/11 era. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nThe Department of Defense has never passed a comprehensive financial audit since audits became mandatory under the Chief Financial Officers Act of 1990. In its most recent audit (FY2023), the DoD again received a disclaimer of opinion. The DoD Inspector General and Government Accountability Office have repeatedly flagged trillions in unsupported accounting adjustments. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nMichigan State University economist Mark Skidmore, in collaboration with former HUD Assistant Secretary Catherine Austin Fitts, published research in 2017 identifying approximately $21 trillion in undocumentable adjustments in DoD and HUD accounts between 1998-2015. Subsequent analysis extended this figure. The Federal Accounting Standards Advisory Board subsequently issued FASAB Statement 56 (2018), which permits federal entities to modify financial statements for national security purposes, effectively legalizing the concealment of spending. [ðŸŸ¡]\n\nCritics including former Senate Intelligence Committee members have argued that waived USAPs create unconstitutional gaps in Congressional oversight, enabling programs to operate without meaningful legislative accountability. The 2023-2024 UAP disclosure legislation (Schumer-Rounds UAPDA) specifically targeted this oversight gap. [ðŸŸ¢]",
