    "fullDescription": "The United States maintains several confirmed deep underground military installations (DUMBs) built primarily during the Cold War for continuity-of-government (COG) operations.\n\nCheyenne Mountain Complex (Colorado Springs, CO) was constructed 1961-1966 inside 2,000 feet of granite, serving as NORAD and US Space Command headquarters. The facility comprises 15 buildings mounted on steel springs to absorb nuclear blast shock, protected by 25-ton blast doors. Though operational functions were relocated to Peterson Air Force Base in 2006, the complex is maintained in 'warm standby' and remains fully operational. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nRaven Rock Mountain Complex (Site R), located near Blue Ridge Summit, Pennsylvania, was built 1951-1953 as the Alternate Joint Communications Center and serves as the backup Pentagon. Garrison strength is approximately 350 personnel. The facility was detailed in Garrett Graff's 'Raven Rock: The Story of the U.S. Government's Secret Plan to Save Itself' (2017), drawing on extensive FOIA research. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nMount Weather Emergency Operations Center (Bluemont, VA) operates under FEMA as the primary COG facility for executive branch relocation. Its existence became publicly known after the 1974 crash of TWA Flight 514 on the mountain. Congressional hearings in 1975 (Senate Subcommittee on Constitutional Rights) revealed details of its parallel governance infrastructure. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nUS Patent 3,693,731, filed May 1971 and granted September 1972, describes a 'Rapid Excavation by Rock Melting' apparatus â€” a nuclear-powered tunnel boring machine (TBM) that melts rock into a glass-like lining using lithium-cooled nuclear reactor heat. Inventors: Dale E. Armstrong and Robert J. Hanold, assigned to the United States Atomic Energy Commission. Whether such devices were ever built or deployed beyond experimental stages remains undocumented. [ðŸŸ¡]\n\nRichard Sauder, PhD, has compiled extensive FOIA research on underground base construction in 'Underground Bases and Tunnels: What Is the Government Trying to Hide?' (1995) and 'Hidden in Plain Sight' (2010), documenting declassified military engineering studies and congressional appropriations for underground construction. Some of his inferences about the scope and connectivity of tunnel networks extend beyond documented evidence. [ðŸŸ¡]",
