    "description": "Government weather modification programs are extensively documented, spanning military operations, international treaties, and ongoing civilian research.\n\nOperation Popeye (also Project Popeye/Motorpool/Intermediary-Compatriot) was a classified US military cloud-seeding campaign conducted over Laos, Vietnam, and Cambodia from 1967 to 1972.",
    "fullDescription": "Government weather modification programs are extensively documented, spanning military operations, international treaties, and ongoing civilian research.\n\nOperation Popeye (also Project Popeye/Motorpool/Intermediary-Compatriot) was a classified US military cloud-seeding campaign conducted over Laos, Vietnam, and Cambodia from 1967 to 1972. The operation used silver iodide and lead iodide dispersal from WC-130 aircraft to extend the monsoon season along the Ho Chi Minh Trail, aiming to soften road surfaces and trigger landslides. It was revealed by journalist Jack Anderson in March 1971 and subsequently confirmed in a classified 1974 Senate hearing. Declassified DoD documents confirm the operation's scope and results. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nThe revelation of Operation Popeye directly catalyzed the Environmental Modification Convention (ENMOD), opened for signature in 1976 and entering into force in 1978. The treaty prohibits military use of environmental modification techniques having 'widespread, long-lasting or severe effects.' The US ratified ENMOD in 1980. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nPublic Law 92-205 (Weather Modification Reporting Act, 1971) required any person engaging in weather modification activities in the US to report to the Secretary of Commerce. This was succeeded by the Weather Modification Research and Development Policy Authorization Act. NOAA maintained a weather modification project reporting database documenting hundreds of cloud-seeding and precipitation-enhancement projects across the US from the 1950s onward. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nThe High-frequency Active Auroral Research Program (HAARP), located in Gakona, Alaska, is an ionospheric research facility originally funded by the Air Force, Navy, and DARPA. Its Ionospheric Research Instrument (IRI) is a 3.6-megawatt high-frequency phased-array transmitter capable of temporarily exciting a limited volume of the ionosphere. HAARP was transferred to the University of Alaska Fairbanks in 2015. Bernard Eastlund's patents (US 4,686,605, filed 1985) described methods of altering the ionosphere and are frequently cited in connection with HAARP, though the operational facility differs significantly from Eastlund's more speculative proposals. [ðŸŸ¢ for facility specs; ðŸŸ¡ for Eastlund weapon-capability claims]\n\nChina's Tianhe ('Sky River') program, announced in 2018 by Tsinghua University and the China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation, proposed using a network of fuel-burning chambers on the Tibetan Plateau to generate silver iodide particles for large-scale precipitation enhancement over an area of 1.6 million square kilometers. The program's operational status and actual results remain unclear as of available reporting. [ðŸŸ¡]",
