    "fullDescription": "The US Public Health Service (USPHS) conducted a 40-year experiment (1932-1972) in which 399 Black men in Macon County, Alabama with syphilis were deliberately denied treatment â€” even after penicillin became the standard cure in 1947 â€” to study the disease's natural progression. An additional 201 men without syphilis served as controls. Participants were told they were receiving free treatment for 'bad blood' [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nDISCLOSURE: USPHS researcher Peter Buxtun repeatedly raised ethical objections internally (1966, 1968) and was ignored. He finally went to the press. AP reporter Jean Heller broke the story on July 25, 1972, ending the study [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nHUMAN COST: By study's end, 128 participants had died of syphilis or its complications. 40 wives were infected. 19 children were born with congenital syphilis [ðŸŸ¢ CDC acknowledgment].\n\nAFTERMATH:\nâ€¢ The National Research Act of 1974 was passed in direct response, establishing the National Commission for the Protection of Human Subjects [ðŸŸ¢].\nâ€¢ The Belmont Report (1979) established core bioethics principles (respect for persons, beneficence, justice) â€” born directly from Tuskegee's horrors [ðŸŸ¢].\nâ€¢ Institutional Review Boards (IRBs) became mandatory for federally funded research [ðŸŸ¢].\nâ€¢ President Clinton formally apologized on May 16, 1997: 'The United States government did something that was wrong â€” deeply, profoundly, morally wrong' [ðŸŸ¢].\nâ€¢ Last participant died in 2004. Last widow died in 2009. A $10M settlement had been reached in 1974 [ðŸŸ¢].\n\nSIGNIFICANCE: Tuskegee is not an isolated incident but part of a documented pattern of government experimentation on vulnerable populations â€” the same USPHS conducted the Guatemala experiments (1946-1948). The study's racial targeting compounds its significance as both a medical ethics violation and an act of institutional racism.",
