    "fullDescription": "The Sackler family, through their privately held Purdue Pharma, engineered one of the deadliest corporate-driven public health catastrophes in American history. In 1996, Purdue introduced OxyContin with an aggressive marketing campaign built on the central claim that its time-release formula made it less addictive than other opioids -- a claim the company knew was misleading and which lacked FDA-approved support. [ðŸŸ¢ DOJ records; court filings] Sales representatives were trained to tell physicians the addiction risk was 'less than one percent.' OxyContin revenue soared from $44 million in 1996 to nearly $3 billion by 2001-2002.\n\nIn 2007, Purdue Pharma and three executives pleaded guilty to federal charges of misbranding OxyContin 'with the intent to defraud or mislead,' paying $634.5 million in fines. [ðŸŸ¢ DOJ press release, WDVA] Despite this conviction, Purdue continued and even intensified its marketing. Court-released internal documents revealed the company systematically tracked high-prescribing doctors and regions with elevated abuse rates, using this data not to flag diversion but to direct sales teams for maximum revenue extraction. [ðŸŸ¢ Court-released internal documents]\n\nThe opioid crisis has killed over 500,000 Americans from opioid overdoses since 1999, with total opioid-involved deaths (including synthetics like fentanyl) reaching approximately 806,000 through 2023. [ðŸŸ¢ CDC WONDER database] In 2020, Purdue pleaded guilty a second time to three federal felony charges -- conspiracy to defraud the United States and two counts of violating the Federal Anti-Kickback Statute -- with agreed penalties of $8.3 billion. [ðŸŸ¢ DOJ]\n\nThe Sackler family extracted approximately $11 billion from Purdue in dividends while the company faced mounting litigation. In bankruptcy proceedings, the Sacklers negotiated personal civil immunity in exchange for contributing roughly $6 billion. The Supreme Court struck down this arrangement in Harrington v. Purdue Pharma (2024), ruling 5-4 that bankruptcy courts cannot grant nonconsensual third-party releases. [ðŸŸ¢ Supreme Court opinion, 23-124] McKinsey & Company, which advised Purdue on strategies to 'turbocharge' OxyContin sales, paid $650 million to the DOJ in December 2024 and over $600 million in prior state settlements. [ðŸŸ¢ DOJ; state AG settlements] The FDA's user-fee-dependent approval process and revolving door with industry facilitated the regulatory failures that enabled the crisis. [ðŸŸ¡ Investigative reporting; academic studies]",
