    "description": "The United States Information and Educational Exchange Act of 1948, commonly known as the Smith-Mundt Act (Public Law 80-402), was signed by President Truman on January 27, 1948 to establish a legal framework for U.S. government public diplomacy and international broadcasting.",
    "fullDescription": "The United States Information and Educational Exchange Act of 1948, commonly known as the Smith-Mundt Act (Public Law 80-402), was signed by President Truman on January 27, 1948 to establish a legal framework for U.S. government public diplomacy and international broadcasting. A central provision of the original act explicitly prohibited the domestic dissemination of materials produced by the State Department and its broadcasting entities â€” including Voice of America â€” that were intended for foreign audiences. The law ensured that government-produced propaganda directed abroad could not be turned inward against American citizens. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nOn January 2, 2013, President Obama signed the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2013 (Public Law 112-239). Buried within this massive defense spending bill was Section 1078 â€” the Smith-Mundt Modernization Act of 2012 (originally introduced as H.R. 5736) â€” co-sponsored by Rep. Mac Thornberry (R-TX) and Rep. Adam Smith (D-WA). This amendment struck the domestic dissemination ban, allowing materials produced by the State Department and the Broadcasting Board of Governors (now the U.S. Agency for Global Media, USAGM) to be made available to audiences within the United States. [ðŸŸ¢]\n\nThe sponsors argued the amendment was necessary to modernize U.S. information operations for the internet age, where foreign-targeted content was already accessible domestically online. Critics countered that the change effectively legalized domestic government propaganda. Content produced by Voice of America, Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty, Radio Free Asia, and the Middle East Broadcasting Networks â€” all funded through USAGM's approximately $810 million annual budget, broadcasting in over 60 languages â€” could now legally target American audiences. [ðŸŸ¡]\n\nThe historical significance is amplified by documented precedent. The Church Committee's 1975 investigation confirmed that the CIA maintained relationships with at least fifty American journalists and had access to numerous media outlets for covert propaganda purposes â€” findings that had originally motivated strict domestic dissemination controls. [ðŸŸ¢] The amendment passed with minimal public debate, embedded within a must-pass defense authorization bill, raising concerns that a fundamental safeguard against government influence over domestic information was quietly dismantled. [ðŸŸ¡]",
