    "fullDescription": "The foundational event in UAP secrecy. In early July 1947, rancher W.W. \"Mac\" Brazel discovered unusual debris scattered across a pasture northwest of Roswell, New Mexico, and reported it to the local sheriff, who contacted Roswell Army Air Field (RAAF). On July 8, 1947, RAAF public information officer Lt. Walter Haut â€” acting on orders from base commander Col. William Blanchard â€” issued a press release stating the 509th Bomb Group had recovered a \"flying disc.\" The story made headlines worldwide. [ðŸŸ¢ original RAAF press release]\n\nWithin hours, Eighth Air Force commander Brig. Gen. Roger Ramey held a press conference at Fort Worth Army Air Field, displaying debris he identified as a conventional weather balloon and radar reflector. Press photographs from this event show Ramey holding a document â€” the so-called \"Ramey Memo\" â€” which, when subjected to modern digital enhancement, has been read by some analysts as containing phrases including \"victims of the wreck,\" though interpretations remain disputed. [ðŸŸ¢ historical photographs] [ðŸŸ¡ photographic analysis, disputed]\n\nMaj. Jesse Marcel, the intelligence officer who first recovered debris from the ranch site, stated in interviews beginning in 1978 (conducted by nuclear physicist Stanton Friedman) that the material was \"not of this Earth\" and that he had been ordered to participate in the cover-up by posing with substituted weather balloon debris. [ðŸŸ¡ Marcel interviews, 1978-1986]\n\nIn 1994, the USAF published \"The Roswell Report: Fact vs. Fiction in the New Mexico Desert,\" attributing the debris to Project Mogul â€” a classified high-altitude balloon program designed to monitor Soviet nuclear tests via acoustic detection. In 1997, a follow-up report, \"The Roswell Report: Case Closed,\" attempted to explain witness accounts of body recoveries by citing anthropomorphic crash test dummies used in Project High Dive. However, researchers noted that High Dive tests did not begin until 1953 â€” six years after the Roswell event â€” creating an unresolved timeline discrepancy. [ðŸŸ¢ USAF reports; timeline discrepancy noted]\n\nCongressman Steven Schiff (R-NM) requested a GAO investigation after the Department of Defense stonewalled his direct inquiries. The resulting 1995 GAO report (NSIAD-95-187) found that RAAF administrative records from March 1945 through December 1949 and outgoing messages from October 1946 through December 1949 had been destroyed. No documentation was found indicating who authorized the destruction or why. [ðŸŸ¢ GAO report]\n\nLt. Walter Haut left a sealed affidavit (signed 2002, opened after his death in 2005) claiming he had personally witnessed alien bodies and a craft stored in Hangar 84 at Roswell. As a posthumous statement, it cannot be cross-examined. [ðŸŸ¡ affidavit, posthumous]",
